I used a raft on the Fretboard so that I could level the show side of the fretboard for a better finish. It is not necessary, but it removes the layer lines that show up otherwise.

Update: Neck and head change required. I could not play some chords well due to the proximity of the tuner for the 1st string. See Gourd Ukulele Body 3v2.stl.

Finishing

Once all the body parts are printed, I assembled them with CA adhesive and accelerator. The spine was not readily available without paying what I thought was too much, so I did the same thing as I did for my previous Ukulele build. I cut a 3mm x 1mm x 1000mm carbon fiber flat into two 500mm lengths and the same thing to a 3mm sq. tube. These were then laminated together with the flats on the outside, thereby making a 3mm x 8mm x 500mm carbon section. This was then installed, trimmed, and sanded flush. Take precautions when sanding carbon fiber. Where a respirator. The dust created sanding this material should not be inhaled or ingested.

I then sanded the entire body starting with a 220 grit all the way down to 1000 grit, leaving the surface nice and smooth. Install the tuning machines, bridge and fretboard. Now you are ready to string the instrument.

description.text:
The micro drone propeller has been designed using the Liebeck L1003 airfoil coordinates. It was tested on the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (results below).

It was printed at a slow speed, with the help of a 0.2 extruder nozzle at 0.04 layer height. I cleaned the final part using a Precision Knife

After this, it was sanded using a 500 grit sandpaper.

These are the thrust measurements for a few voltage values (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 6.76 grams
  • 2V => 12.47 grams
  • 2.5V => 21.37 grams
  • 3V => 27.57 grams

The files you can download consist of all the pictures taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. Should you want to play with this propeller, make sure you have a few 8520 coreless motors.

Use the SLDPRT extension files, in case you wish to adapt the propeller model to suit your own needs.

Notice: The airfoil plotted with the matplotlib library for python.

Once the spacecraft design is finished they create a 3D printable model of the spacecraft.
This project was completed with a 7th grade class as part of a unit on the Solar System.

• Teams choose a target for the mission to search for life in the solar system (see lab report).
  • Students use the cards and design mat (from ASU website) and the spreadsheet to design their spacecraft. Spacecraft must have the equipment needed to complete the mission without exceeding the limits on $, weight, and power.
  • Students turn in their completed spreadsheet for review and answer the question on the lab report.
  • When their design is approved they use Tinkercad to create a 3D printable model of their spacecraft.

This is a housing design for an Atari 2600/VCS cartridge. It will hold a standard Atari PCB or suitable replacement (like my homebrew PCB design: www.grandideastudio.com/portfolio/pixels-past/) This was co-designed back in 2002 with the friendly fellows from www.toolinc.com, but never saw the light of day (until now!) See a time-lapse video of the Makerbotting and assembly in action at http://youtu.be/Ngb69HvGE7g

Print all three pieces, insert PCB, press fit together, secure with a single screw, plug into Atari, GAME!
Make sure your platform is level. The top and bottom housings take up most of the space on the Thing-o-Matic build platform and if there is uneven heating, the housing will warp and won't fit into the Atari very well (like the one I made). 
The snaps along the housing edges are pretty brittle and the label area comes out a bit funky as it's recessed a bit. I had the best results at 100% infill and 1 shell. 
Looks especially swell in any color other than the typical Atari cartridge color of black.

title: S8064 Q500 Pylon Racing Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (38.17g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
The propeller has been designed by using the S8064 Q500 Pylon Racing airfoil coordinates. I tested it on the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Tester (results below).

It was printed slowly, by using a 0.2mm extruder nozzle at 0.04 height per layer. The print was cleaned with a Precision Knife

After this, I got to finishing the part with a 400 grit sandpaper.

Here are the measurements for a few voltage values (these can also be viewed in the image files):

  • 1.5V => 10.57 grams
  • 2V => 19.64 grams
  • 2.5V => 28.11 grams
  • 3V => 38.17 grams

The files you can download contain all shots taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. Should you want to tinker with this propeller, you need to get a bunch of 8520 coreless motors.

You can use the SLDPRT files, should you want to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

Notes: Airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library for python.

title: Tenkara Line Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I am an advocate of tenkara - a form of traditional Japanese fly fishing. Modern Tenkara rods telescope and the line is a fixed length, usually around 12'. Between fishing, the line needs to be stored. This line holder does just that and then slips over the cork grip on the rod. It is similar to commercial Japanese versions but mine is smaller and wider and made of biodegradable PLA!  
UPDATE: I realized that this thing did not need to be so wide, so I've created a narrower version that is 5mm between the spool flanges. The original is 10mm between flanges. I like this narrower version much better.

Print in your favorite material - PLA is renewable and biodegradable. Both parts are printed together for convenience. Once printed, I like to sand the edges slightly and the insides of the 8 slots to make sure they do not snag the line. Glue it together with super glue or epoxy.  
I am working on a snap together version.  
Print them in different colors so you can tell your different lines apart.
